{"title_page": "Moringa stenopetala", "text_new": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Moringa stenopetala - Fruit and Spice Park - Homestead, Florida - DSC08808.jpg\n| image_caption = A specimen at the [[Fruit and Spice Park]] in [[Redland, Florida]]\n| image2 = Moringa stenopetala flowers and leaves.jpg\n| image2_caption = Flowers and leaves, photographed on [[Oahu]], [[Hawaii]]\n| genus = Moringa\n| species = stenopetala\n| authority = ([[Edmund Gilbert Baker|Baker f.]]) [[Georg Cufodontis|Cufod.]]<ref name=\"grin1\">&nbsp;Under its current treatment of ''Moringa stenopetala'' (from its basionym, ''Donaldsonia stenopetala''), this species was published in ''Senckenbergiana Biologica'' 38: 407. 1957. {{GRIN | accessdate=January 1, 2012}}</ref>\n| synonyms  = *''Donaldsonia stenopetala'' <small>Baker f.</small> ([[basionym]])\n* ''Moringa streptocarpa'' <small>[[Emilio Chiovenda|Chiov.]]</small>\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=grin1/><ref name=\"grin2\">&nbsp;The basionym of ''Moringa stenopetala'', ''Donaldsonia stenopetala'', was first described and published in ''Journal of Botany, British and Foreign'' 1896: 53. 1896. {{GRIN | ''Donaldsonia stenopetala'' | 424400 | accessdate = January 1, 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Moringa stenopetala''''', commonly known as the '''African Moringa''' or '''cabbage tree''', is a [[deciduous]] tree in the [[flowering plant]] genus ''[[Moringa]]'', native to [[Kenya]] and [[Ethiopia]].<ref name=\"AAA2015\">{{cite journal | authors = Leone, A.; Spada, A.; Battezzati, A.; Schiraldi, A.; Aristil, J.; Bertoli, S. | title = Cultivation, genetic, ethnopharmacology, phytochemistry and pharmacology of ''Moringa oleifera'' leaves: An overview | journal = International Journal of Molecular Sciences | volume = 16 | pages = 12791\u201312835 | year = 2015 | doi = 10.3390/ijms160612791 | pmid=26057747 | pmc=4490473}}</ref> A drought-resistant species, it is characterized by its bottle-shaped trunk, long twisted [[wikt:seedpod|seed pods]], and  edible leaves likened to [[cabbage]], from which its common name is derived. ''M. stenopetala'' is extirpated in the wild in Ethiopia, though still grown there as a crop on the [[Terrace (agriculture)|terraces]] of the [[Ethiopian Highlands]], mainly in the [[Konso]] region.\n\nLike its widely cultivated relative ''[[Moringa oleifera|M. oleifera]]'', ''Moringa stenopetala'' is a [[multipurpose tree]]: the leaves, pods, and flowers are edible and nutritious; the seeds contain an aromatic oil with culinary and cosmetic applications; and the seed [[press cake]] or powdered bark can be used for [[water purification]]. It is featured in various dishes and has a history of uses in [[folk medicine]] throughout its native range.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe species was first [[Species description|described]] as ''Donaldsonia stenopetala'' by [[botanist]] [[Edmund Gilbert Baker|Edmund G. Baker]] in 1896, based on the [[type specimen]] collected by [[Arthur Donaldson Smith|Donaldson Smith]] along the northeastern shore of [[Lake Turkana]].<ref name=Baker>{{cite journal|author=Baker, E. G|year=1896|title=New African Plants|journal=Journal of Botany, British and Foreign|volume=34|pages=53\u201357|publisher=West, Newman & Co|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/35905#page/68/mode/1up}}</ref> [[Emilio Chiovenda]] later described another specimen from Kenya as ''Moringa streptocarpa''. In 1957, Georg Cufodontis identified these specimens to be [[Morphology (biology)|morphologically]] similar and designated them as ''Moringa stenopetala'', the officially accepted species name.<ref name=Habtemariam>{{cite book|authors=Habtemariam, S.|year=2017|title=The African and Arabian Moringa Species|chapter=1: ''Moringa stenopetala''\u2014Botanical and Ecological Perspectives|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=9780081022948|edition=1|pages=3\u201312}}</ref> The specific epithet ''stenopetala'' is derived from the [[Greek language|Greek]] words ''stenos'' (narrow or straight) and ''petalum'' (petal), a reference to the shape of its [[petal]]s.<ref name=botdict>{{cite web|url=http://www.botanicalepithets.net/dictionary/dictionary.171.html|work=Dictionary of Botanical Epithets|title=stella - stolonifer|year=2019|accessdate=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n\nAlong with at least twelve other species, ''M. stenopetala'' belongs to the [[Monotypic taxon|monotypic genus]] ''[[Moringa]]'', which is the sole representative of the family [[Moringaceae]]. Researchers have divided these species into three distinct groups: ''Moringa'' with eight, ''Dysmoringa'' with one, and ''Donadsonia'' with four.<ref name=Habtemariam /><ref name=Olson2001>{{cite book|authors=Lianli, L.; Olson, M.E|year=2001|chapter=Moringaceae|editors=P.H. Raven, I. Al-Shehbaz & G. Zhu|title=Flora of China (Brassicaceae through Saxifragaceae)|series=Flora of China|volume=8|page=196|publisher=Missouri Botanical Garden Press|isbn=9780915279937}}</ref> ''M. stenopetala'' belongs to the latter group, along with ''[[Moringa drouhardii|M. drouhardii]]'' and ''[[Moringa hildebrandtii|M. hildebrandtii]]'', characterized by winged seeds and (almost) regular flowers with short [[Receptacle (botany)|receptacles]] and [[Ovary (botany)#Superior ovary|superior ovaries]].<ref name=Habtemariam />\n\n''M. stenopetala'' is known under various [[Common name|vernacular name]]s throughout its native regions, including ''(h)aleko'' in the [[Gidole]] language ([[Gamo Gofa Zone|Gamo Gofa]]), ''shelagda'' or ''telchada'' in the [[Konso language]], and ''Shiferaw'' in [[Amharic]]. In English, it is most commonly known as the African Moringa or cabbage tree, though these names may be shared with other ''Moringa'' species from Africa.<ref name=Habtemariam />\n\n==Description==\n[[File:First illustration of Moringa stenopetala (basonym Donaldsonia), from E. G. Baker's 1896 original description.jpg|165px|thumb|left|Illustration from the ''[[Journal of Botany, British and Foreign]]'' in 1896]] \n''Moringa stenopetala'' is a [[perennial]] tree with a [[shrub]]by, rounded [[Habit (biology)|habit]],<ref name=seednutrition>{{cite journal|title=Characterisation of ''Moringa stenopetala'' seed oil variety \"Marigat\" from island Kokwa|authors=Lalas, S.; Tsaknis, J.; Sflomos, K.|year=2003|journal=European Journal of Lipid Science and Technology|volume=105|issue=1|pages=23\u201331|doi=10.1002/ejlt.200390002}}</ref> growing to a height of {{convert|6|-|12|m|0|abbr=on}} in all but the most exceptional cases where it may reach   {{convert|15|m|0|abbr=on}} high.<ref name=WAF /><ref name=ECHO>{{cite web|url=https://www.echocommunity.org/en/resources/8b52cd0f-d585-45df-905e-a93fa631a8bf.pdf|title=African Moringa Tree|work=Echo Plant Information Sheet|year=2019|publisher=ECHO}}</ref> [[wikt:caudiciform|Caudiciform]] or \"bottle shaped\",<ref name=PROTA2>{{cite book|title=Plant Resources of Tropical Africa|series=Plant Resources of Tropical Africa (PROTA)|volume=2: Vegetables|editors=G.J.H. Grubben & O.A. Denton|year=2004|publisher=Earthprint Limited|author=Bosch, C.H.|chapter=Moringa|pages=395\u2212398|isbn=9789057821486}}</ref> the trunk is bloated at the base and habitually [[Tree fork|forked]],<ref name=WAF /> with a diameter up to {{convert|1|m|0|abbr=on}}. The bark is smooth and whitish to light gray or silver, harboring soft wood underneath.<ref name=PROTA2 /> The crown is sprawling and heavily branched; younger shoots are characterized by a dense, velvety [[indumentum|pubescence]].<ref name=floraEA>{{cite book|title=Flora of Tropical East Africa|chapter=Moringaceae|series=Flora of Tropical East Africa|publisher=CRC Press|year=1986|editor=R. M. Polhill|author=Verdcourt, B.|issue=80|isbn=978-1842463970}}</ref>\n\nThe leaves are light green when mature,<ref name=PGR-Ethiopia>{{cite book|chapter=Konso agriculture and its plant genetic resources|title=Plant Genetic Resources of Ethiopia|year=1991|publisher=Cambridge University Press|editors=J.M.M. Engels, J.G. Hawkes & M. Worede|authors=Engels, J.M.M.; Goettsch, E.|edition=1|isbn=978-0521384568}}</ref> up to {{convert|55|cm|0|abbr=on}} long, and [[Phyllotaxis#Leaf arrangement|attached alternately]] to the stem by short [[Petiole (botany)|petiole]]s.<ref name=PROTA2 /> They are bi- or tri[[Pinnation|pinnate]] in composition, with about five pairs of pinnae and three to nine [[Leaflet (botany)|leaflets]] on each pinna.<ref name=WAF>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldagroforestry.org/treedb/AFTPDFS/Moringa_stenopetala.PDF|title=''Moringa stenopetala''|work=Agroforestry Database 4.0|year=2009|publisher=World Agroforestry}}</ref> Each leaflet is {{convert|3.5|-|6.5|cm|1|abbr=on}} \u00d7 {{convert|2|-|3.5|cm|1|abbr=on}} in size and [[wikt:elliptical|elliptical]] to [[wikt:ovate|ovate]] in shape, with an [[Leaf shapes|acute]] tip and a round-to-[[wikt:cuneate|cuneate]] base.<ref name=PROTA2 /> [[Stipule]]-like [[extrafloral nectaries]] are typically present at the base of the leaves.<ref name=PROTA2 /><ref name=bottleforms>{{cite web|url=http://www.mobot.org/gradstudents/olson/bottlespecies.html|title=Bottle Tree Form|website=Moringa Home Page|publisher=Missouri Botanical Garden|year=1999|author=Olson, M.}}</ref>\n\n''M. stenopetala'' features a busy, aromatic [[inflorescence]], organized as dense [[panicle]]s up to {{convert|60|cm|0|abbr=on}} long. The individual flowers are [[Plant reproductive morphology#bisexual|bisexual]], [[Radial symmetry|radially symmetrical]], and [[Merosity|pentamerous]]. The [[Calyx (botany)|calyx]] is [[wikt:polysepalous|polysepalous]] and cream colored, sometimes flushed pink, with {{convert|4|-|7|mm|1|abbr=on}} long [[sepal]]s. The [[Catacorolla|corolla]] is [[wikt:polypetalous|polypetalous]] and variably white, pale-yellow or yellow-green; its petals are roughly oblong in shape and {{convert|8|-|10|mm|1|abbr=on}} in length.<ref name=PROTA2 /> Each flower features five [[stamen]]s with white {{convert|4|-|6.5|mm|1|abbr=on}} long filaments and yellow {{convert|2|mm|1|abbr=on}} long anthers, as well as an indeterminate number of shorter [[staminode]]s.<ref name=floraEA /> The [[Ovary (botany)|ovary]] is densely haired and [[Superior ovary|superior]], {{convert|2|mm|1|abbr=on}} long and [[wikt:ovoid|ovoid]] in shape, transitioning to a smooth cylindrical [[Stylodia|style]] sans [[Stigma (botany)#Shape|stigmatic lobes]].<ref name=PROTA2 />\n\nThe fruits comprise {{convert|19.7|-|50|cm|1|abbr=on}} \u00d7 {{convert|1.8|-|4|cm|1|abbr=on}} elongate pods which are initially twisted but gradually straight, sometimes [[wikt:torose|torose]] (bulbous) around the encapsulated seeds.<ref name=floraEA /> Young pods are bright green,<ref name=moringaceae /> maturing to a reddish coloration with a grayish bloom.<ref name=floraEA /> The fruits are [[Dehiscence (botany)|dehiscent]], splitting open along three prominent [[Glossary of botanical terms#valve|valves]] when mature and releasing up to 20 seeds each.<ref name=seeds>{{cite journal|title=The potential of some ''Moringa'' species for seed oil production|journal=Agriculture|year=2018|volume=8|issue=10|page=150|authors=Boukandoul, S.; Casal, S.; Zaidi, F.|doi=10.3390/agriculture8100150}}</ref> Covered by a cream to brownish husk with three papery wings, the seeds are oblong to triangular, {{convert|2.5|-|3.5|cm|1|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|1.5|-|2|cm|1|abbr=on}} wide,<ref name=PROTA2 /> containing a smooth, whitish grey kernel.<ref name=seeds />\n\n== Distribution, habitat and ecology ==\nSparsely [[Range (biology)|distributed]] across the [[Horn of Africa]],<ref name=bottleforms /> ''Moringa stenopetala'' is [[Endemism|endemic]] to southern [[Ethiopia]], northern [[Kenya]],<ref name=PROTA2 /> and possibly [[Somalia]].<ref name=WAF /><ref name=Star>{{cite journal|title=\n''Moringa stenopetala'' tree species improved selected soil properties and socio-economic benefits in Tigray, northern Ethiopia|journal=Science, Technology and Arts Research Journal|year=2015|authors= Abay, A.; Birhane, E.; Taddesse, T.; Hagdu, K.M.|doi=10.4314/star.v4i2.10|volume=4|issue=2|pages=68\u201378}}</ref> Extant populations are poorly documented,<ref name=bottleforms /> but have been identified in the wild in at least five localities across the [[Great Rift Valley, Kenya|Kenyan Rift Valley]]<ref name=PROTA2 />\u2014one on [[Ol Kokwe Island]] in [[Lake Baringo]] and four around the shores of [[Lake Turkana]].<ref name=bottleforms /> Records of wild specimens from other east African countries, including [[Djibouti]], [[Sudan]], and [[Uganda]], have been deemed unreliable.   ''M. stenopetala'' trees are widely cultivated in southern Ethiopia, where they were likely sourced from a now-extinct population near [[Lake Chew Bahir]].<ref name=PROTA2/> Since modern times, the species has steadily been [[Introduced species|introduced]] across tropical Africa: it is found as far west as [[Senegal]] and as far south as [[Malawi]].<ref name=PROTA2 />\n\n[[File:Ethiopia - Mature Moringa stenopetala tree - March 2011.jpg|thumb|right|[[Habit (biology)|Habit]] in the [[Gurage Zone]], Ethiopia]] \nIn the wild, ''M. stenopetala'' occurs in various [[habitats]] with different [[Bioclimatology|bioclimatic]] conditions and [[elevation]]s of 400\u20131,200&nbsp;m (1,300\u20133,900&nbsp;ft).<ref name=WAF /><ref name=floraEA /> Its distribution range is [[Arid climate|arid]] to [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]], with an average annual rainfall of 500\u20131,400&nbsp;mm (20\u201355&nbsp;in) and mean temperatures of 24\u201330&nbsp;\u00b0C (75\u201386&nbsp;\u00b0F).<ref name=WAF /> Often growing near bodies of water,<ref name=PROTA2/> wild trees have been observed in [[dryland]]s, [[shrubland]]s, and [[woodland]]s,<ref name=floraEA /> where they may form [[Association (ecology)|associations]] with ''[[Acacia tortilis]]'', ''[[Delonix elata]]'' and ''[[Commiphora]]'' spp.,<ref name=WAF /> as well as in [[wetland]]s, often associated with riverside species from ''[[Hyphaene]]'', ''[[Salvadora (plant)|Salvadora]]'' and ''[[Cadaba]]''.<ref name=floraEA /> These regions are characterized by rocky or sandy soils,<ref name=PROTA2/><ref name=moringaceae /> with good [[drainage]] and neutral to slightly acidic or alkaline [[soil pH|soil reaction]].<ref name=WAF /> The species is, however, known for its ability to subsist on a wide variety of (possibly very harsh) soil conditions;<ref name=WAF /><ref name=Star /> mature trees can even improve the [[soil fertility|fertility]] of the surrounding topsoil with their tendency to shed considerable amounts of [[Soil organic matter|organic matter]].<ref name=Star />\n\nLike its African relatives, ''M. stenopetala'' is well adapted to the severe heat and drought that characterize its native landscapes,<ref name=moringaceae /> where, given proper shading, it may survive temperatures up to 48&nbsp;\u00b0C (118&nbsp;\u00b0F).<ref name=Star /> Developing early, the tuberous roots and bloated trunk form a prominent [[storage organ]],<ref name=moringaceae /> which allows the plant to preserve water and thrive in drier climates.<ref name=Habtemariam /> Although drought-[[deciduous]], shedding its leaves towards the end of very prolonged dry seasons, it habitually grows as an [[evergreen]] under more moderate conditions.<ref name=Habtemariam /><ref name=lostcrops /> Light frost is tolerated, although persistent cold temperatures at higher growing elevations may eventually cause the tree to wither down to the base of its trunk, as well as inducing [[Seed dormancy|dormancy]] in seeds.<ref name=WAF /><ref name=Star/>\n\n''M. stenopetala'' trees live between 60 and 100&nbsp;years, often with sustained productivity until the end of their lifespan.<ref name=seifu>{{cite journal|authors=Seifu, E.|year=2014|title=Actual and potential applications of ''Moringa stenopetala'', underutilized indigenous vegetable of Southern Ethiopia: A review|journal=International Journal of Agricultural and Food Research|volume=3|issue=4|pages=8\u201319|ISSN=1929-0969}}</ref>  It is a quickly developing species; young plants can grow as high as 3&nbsp;m (10&nbsp;ft) in their first year and typically reach [[Plant reproduction|reproductive maturity]] after 2.5&nbsp;years.<ref name=PROTA2 /> From there on, the plants often continue to flower and fruit year-round.<ref name=Star /> The flowers emit a sweet fragrance that encourages [[pollination]] by birds and insects alike.<ref name=moringaceae>{{cite book|author=Kubitzki, K.|year=2003|chapter=Moringaceae|editors=K. Kubitzki & C. Bayer|title=Flowering Plants \u00b7 Dicotyledons|series=The Families and Genera of Vascular Plants|volume=5|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-662-07255-4}}</ref> Mature seeds may be dispersed by either wind or water.<ref name=moringaceae /> The foliage provides nutritious [[forage]] for both wild and domesticated [[ruminants]], whereas the flowers serve as an important source of [[nectar]] for [[honeybees]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019|reason=removed citation to predatory publisher content}}\n\n==Cultivation==\n''Moringa stenopetala'' was planted by agriculturalists on the complex system of [[Terrace (agriculture)|terraces]] built high up in the [[Ethiopian Highlands]], where they became domesticated and were bred to improve productivity, the taste of their leaves, and the size of their seeds. Since then, the improved trees have been introduced into other areas such as the [[Great Rift Valley, Kenya|Kenyan Rift Valley]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Jahn, S.A.A.|year=1991 |title=The traditional domestication of a multipurpose tree ''Moringa stenopetala'' (Bak. f.) Cuf. in the Ethiopian Rift Valley |journal=Ambio |volume=20 |issue=6 |pages=244\u2013247 |jstor=4313833 }}</ref>\n\nIn present-day Ethiopia, ''M. stenopetala'' is mostly known for its importance as a nutritious [[vegetable]] food crop in the terraced fields of [[Konso]], where it is cultivated for its leaves and pods.<ref name=PROTA2 /> [[Plant propagation|Propagation]] is easiest from seeds,<ref name=Habtemariam /> although plants grown from [[Cutting (plant)|cuttings]] may flower and fruit sooner (within several months).<ref name=lostcrops>{{cite book|title=Vegetables|series=Lost Crops of Africa|volume=2|chapter=14: Moringa|year=2006|publisher=The National Academies Press|isbn=978-0-309-16454-2|pages=246\u2013267}}</ref> Kept moist and in full sun, seeds placed 1\u20132 cm deep in well-draining soil typically [[Germination|germinate]] about a week after sowing. Temperatures for optimal growth and production in the Ethiopian Rift Valley range from 15&nbsp;\u00b0C (59&nbsp;\u00b0F) to 33&nbsp;\u00b0C (91&nbsp;\u00b0F), corresponding with elevations of 1,150\u20131,800&nbsp;m (3,775\u20135,900&nbsp;ft). Collection of the leaves and fruits may start after two years, although traditional farmers usually wait 5 to 6 years before harvesting.<ref name=Habtemariam />\n\n==Culinary use and nutrition ==\n<!--{{Nutritional value\n| name = Nutritional composition of ''Moringa stenopetala'' leaf, raw\n| kJ = 295\n| protein = 9.0\n| fat = 5.8\n| carbs = 51.8\n| vitC_mg = 28.07\n| calcium_mg = 793\n| iron_mg = 3.08\n| phosphorus_mg = 65.6\n| potassium_mg = 453.0\n| sodium_mg = 403.5\n| zinc_mg = 0.53\n}} -->\n\nThe leaves, seeds, flowers and young pods of ''M. stenopetala'' are all edible and commonly feature in dishes across its distribution range. Over 5&nbsp;million people are estimated to consume ''M. stenopetala'' on a regular basis;<ref name=PROTA2 /> it is especially favored by various ethnic groups of Ethiopia's [[Southern Nations, Nationalities, and Peoples' Region|SNNP Region]].<ref name=PROTA2 /><ref name=Kumssa /><ref name=dishes />\n\n=== Leaves ===\n[[File:Moringa stenopetala.jpg|thumb|Leaves on a young plant, showing a [[Pinnation|pinnate]] composition]]\nLike ''M. oleifera'', the leaves of ''M. stenopetala'' make for a nutrient-dense edible green. A [[nutrition analysis]] of an Ethiopian sample yielded 28.44&nbsp;g of protein, 0.7&nbsp;g of fat, 38.49&nbsp;g of [[carbohydrate]]s and 11.62&nbsp;g of crude fiber per 100&nbsp;g dry weight, with a mean energy value of 274&nbsp;[[Calorie|kcal]] (1,146 [[Kilojoule|kJ]]).{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} Raw leaves are rich in [[vitamin C]] (28&nbsp;mg/100&nbsp;g), a good source of [[vitamin A]], and comparable to [[cruciferous vegetables]] for their significant mineral content (such as [[calcium]], [[iron]] and [[phosphorus]]).<ref name=WAF /><ref name=PROTA2 /> Within the ''Moringa'', ''M. stenopetala'' leaves are highest in [[sulfur]] and remarkably rich in protein.<ref name=olson2016>{{cite journal|title=Leaf protein and mineral concentrations across the \"miracle tree\" genus ''Moringa''|authors=Olson, M.E.; Sankaran, R.P.; Fahey, J.W.; Grusak, M.A.; Odee, D.; Nouman, W.|year=2016|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0159782|journal=PLOS One|volume=11|issue=7|page=e0159782|pmc=4961408}}</ref> Variables that may affect the nutrient \u2013 particularly mineral \u2013 compositions of ''M. stenopetala'' include the season,<ref name=elevation>{{cite journal|title=Effects of elevation and season on nutrient composition of leaves and green pods of ''Moringa stenopetala'' and ''Moringa oleifera''|authors=Melesse, A.; Steingass, H.; Boguhn, J.; Schollenberger, M.; Rodehutscord, M.|journal=Agroforestry Systems|year=2012|volume=86|issue=3|pages=505\u2013518|doi=10.1007/s10457-012-}}</ref> growing elevations,<ref name=elevation /> and soil type.<ref name=Kumssa /> During the dry season, the average southern Ethiopian adult eats 150&nbsp;g of fresh leaves per day, providing 19% of their energy and 30% of their protein requirements.<ref name=PROTA2 />\n\nThe taste of the leaves ranges from bitter to sweet, may vary per tree, and is described as more pleasant during the dry season. The leaflets are stripped from the [[rachis]] and eaten either raw or cooked like [[cabbage]],<ref name=PROTA2 /> inspiring the common name \"cabbage tree\".<ref name=cabbage>{{cite book|chapter=A multipurpose cabbage tree (''Moringa stenopetala''): Production, utilization and marketing in SNNPR, Ethiopia|work=Acta Horticulturae|title=International Symposium on the Socio-Economic Impact of Modern Vegetable Production Technology in Tropical Asia|number=809|isbn=9789066057210|year=2009|volume=1|pages=115\u2013120|authors=Tenaye, A.; Geta, E.; Hebana, E.|editors=H. Jaenicke, J. Ganry, I. Hoeschle-Zeledon & R. Kahane}}</ref> They may be served with bread as a nutritious addition to many meals.<ref name=Kumssa>{{cite journal|title=Challenges and opportunities for ''Moringa'' growers in southern Ethiopia and Kenya|authors=Kumssa, D.B.; Joy, E.J.M.; Young, S.D.; Odee, D.W.; Ander, E.L.; Magare, C.; Gitu, J.; Broadley, M.R.|year=2017|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0187651|journal=PLOS One|volume=12|issue=11|page=e0187651}}</ref><ref name=dishes>{{cite thesis|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/c7d7/e4a605e3093a61c3ad9e538cbafd2c465b6d.pdf|title=Usage and acceptance of ''Moringa stenopetala'' in the diet in Ethiopia|year=2012|author=Gl\u00e6rum, N.|type=MSc|publisher=University of Agder}}</ref> In the Konso region of Ethiopia, balls of mixed flours \u2013 and sometimes cereals \u2013 are typically boiled in salt water and served alongside the leaves.<ref name=PROTA2 /> The [[Silt\u02bce people]] use [[cornmeal]] as the principle flour, and include onions and chilies to create a dish called ''kurkufa''. In a variation of this preparation, known as ''fosesae'', the cornmeal is first mixed with water to create a doughy consistency, and then cooked with the leaves and spices.<ref name=dishes /> Dried, crushed leaves may be added to ''chegga'', a traditional [[sorghum]] brew of the [[Dirashe special woreda|Dirashe people]].<ref name=Kumssa />\n\n=== Other parts ===\nBecause the fruits are slightly bitter, even when young, they are normally prepared only in times when other crops are scarce.<ref name=PROTA2 />\nThe flowers may also be boiled or eaten fresh.<ref name=Kumssa /> The seeds yield an aromatic, edible oil that may be used for cooking or as a dressing for salads.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019|reason=removed citation to predatory publisher content}}\n\n==Other uses==\n[[File:Moringa stenopetala nursery in Gurage Zone, Ethiopia.jpg|thumb|left|''M. stenopetala'' [[Plant nursery|nursery]] in the [[Gurage Zone]] of Ethiopia]]\nIt is used for shading of ''[[Capsicum]]'' and ''[[Sorghum]]'' crops, and as a [[companion planting|companion plant]].<ref name=grin1/>\nA 2015 survey across Derashe and Konso villages found that most households grow ''M. stenopetala'' trees, having done so their entire life; all had consumed the tree as food, many relied on it for income, and some used it for medicinal purposes.<ref name=Kumssa />\n\nAnother use is the clarification and purification of water to make it potable. A powder made by grinding the seeds is found to be more effective at coagulating substances in suspension than the seeds of ''M. oleifera'', which is used for this purpose in India.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3362/0262-8104.1985.019 |title=Water purification with ''Moringa'' seeds |year=1985 |last1=Desa |first1=D. |journal=Waterlines |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=22\u20133}}</ref> When powdered, the tree bark has [[Adsorption|adsorbent]] properties which may be effective in industrial wastewater treatments.<ref name=barkpowder>{{cite journal|title=''Moringa stenopetala'' bark: A novel green adsorbent for the removal of metal ions from industrial effluents|authors=Kebede, T.G.; Dube, S.; Mengistie, A.A.; Nkambule, T.T.I.; Nindia, M.M.|year=2018|journal=Physics and Chemistry of the Earth|volume=107|pages=45\u201357|doi=10.1016/j.pce.2018.08.002}}</ref>\n\n===Folk medicine===\n''M. stenopetala'' has a history of purported applications in [[folk medicine]] throughout its native range. The [[Ilchamus people]] of Kenya chew or boil the roots for cough relief and strength. Among the [[Turkana people]], those with [[leprosy]] drink a [[decoction]] of the leaves.<ref name=PROTA2 /> The macerated roots and/or leaves are boiled in water and taken as a herbal remedy throughout southern Ethiopia for various conditions, such as [[malaria]], [[diarrhea]], and [[dysentery]].<ref name=PROTA2 /><ref name=ethiopia>{{cite book|author=Mekonnen, Y.|chapter=The multi-purpose Moringa tree: Ethiopia|pages=111\u2013117|title=Examples of the Development of Pharmaceutical Products from Medicinal Plants|publisher=United Nations Development Programme|year=2005|volume=10|series=[http://www.esupp.unsouthsouth.org/gssd-academy-solutions/ Sharing Innovative Experiences]|issn=1728-4171}}</ref> The [[Konso people]] use the dried leaves to make a tea or herbal extract, which they believe to have a soothing effect on respiratory ailments.<ref name=PGR-Ethiopia /> Sap extracts from the branches and leaves may be applied externally by the Dirashe people to promote hygiene.<ref name=Kumssa />\n\n== Research ==\nLike its sister species ''M. oleifera'', ''Moringa stenopetala'' is under [[basic research]] to determine whether it has bioactive properties;<ref name=PROTA2 /> its potential effects in humans remain unconfirmed.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160\">\n\nFile:Moringa stenopetala tree trunk, Koko Crater Botanical Garden.jpg|The bloated water-storing trunk of a fully grown tree at [[Koko Crater Botanical Garden]] on [[Oahu]], [[Hawaii]]\nFile:Moringa stenopetala seed pods in tree.jpg|Branches with foliage and fruits at Koko Crater Botanical Garden\nFile:Moringa stenopetala open seed pod.jpg|Open ''M. stenopetala'' fruit pod revealing mature seeds inside\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\nOther African moringa species:\n* ''[[Moringa drouhardii]]\n* ''[[Moringa hildebrandtii]]\n* ''[[Moringa ovalifolia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3021919}}\n\n[[Category:Moringa|streptocarpa]]\n[[Category:Flora of Kenya]]\n[[Category:Trees of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Trees of Africa]]\n[[Category:Fruits originating in Africa]]\n[[Category:Tropical fruit]]\n[[Category:Tropical agriculture]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1896]]\n[[Category:Afromontane flora]]\n", "text_old": "{{Speciesbox\n| image = Moringa stenopetala - Fruit and Spice Park - Homestead, Florida - DSC08808.jpg\n| image_caption = A specimen at the [[Fruit and Spice Park]] in [[Redland, Florida]]\n| image2 = Moringa stenopetala flowers and leaves.jpg\n| image2_caption = Flowers and leaves, photographed on [[Oahu]], [[Hawaii]]\n| genus = Moringa\n| species = stenopetala\n| authority = ([[Edmund Gilbert Baker|Baker f.]]) [[Georg Cufodontis|Cufod.]]<ref name=\"grin1\">&nbsp;Under its current treatment of ''Moringa stenopetala'' (from its basionym, ''Donaldsonia stenopetala''), this species was published in ''Senckenbergiana Biologica'' 38: 407. 1957. {{GRIN | accessdate=January 1, 2012}}</ref>\n| synonyms  = *''Donaldsonia stenopetala'' <small>Baker f.</small> ([[basionym]])\n* ''Moringa streptocarpa'' <small>[[Emilio Chiovenda|Chiov.]]</small>\n| synonyms_ref = <ref name=grin1/><ref name=\"grin2\">&nbsp;The basionym of ''Moringa stenopetala'', ''Donaldsonia stenopetala'', was first described and published in ''Journal of Botany, British and Foreign'' 1896: 53. 1896. {{GRIN | ''Donaldsonia stenopetala'' | 424400 | accessdate = January 1, 2012}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Moringa stenopetala''''', commonly known as the '''African Moringa''' or '''cabbage tree''', is a [[deciduous]] tree in the [[flowering plant]] genus ''[[Moringa]]'', native to [[Kenya]] and [[Ethiopia]].<ref name=\"AAA2015\">{{cite journal | authors = Leone, A.; Spada, A.; Battezzati, A.; Schiraldi, A.; Aristil, J.; Bertoli, S. | title = Cultivation, genetic, ethnopharmacology, phytochemistry and pharmacology of ''Moringa oleifera'' leaves: An overview | journal = International Journal of Molecular Sciences | volume = 16 | pages = 12791\u201312835 | year = 2015 | doi = 10.3390/ijms160612791 | pmid=26057747 | pmc=4490473}}</ref> A drought-resistant species, it is characterized by its bottle-shaped trunk, long twisted [[wikt:seedpod|seed pods]], and  edible leaves likened to [[cabbage]], from which its common name is derived. ''M. stenopetala'' is extirpated in the wild in Ethiopia, though still grown there as a crop on the [[Terrace (agriculture)|terraces]] of the [[Ethiopian Highlands]], mainly in the [[Konso]] region. \n\nLike its widely cultivated relative ''[[Moringa oleifera|M. oleifera]]'', ''Moringa stenopetala'' is a [[multipurpose tree]]: the leaves, pods, and flowers are edible and nutritious; the seeds contain an aromatic oil with culinary and cosmetic applications; and the seed [[press cake]] or powdered bark can be used for [[water purification]]. It is featured in various dishes and has a history of uses in [[folk medicine]] throughout its native range.\n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThe species was first [[Species description|described]] as ''Donaldsonia stenopetala'' by [[botanist]] [[Edmund Gilbert Baker|Edmund G. Baker]] in 1896, based on the [[type specimen]] collected by [[Arthur Donaldson Smith|Donaldson Smith]] along the northeastern shore of [[Lake Turkana]].<ref name=Baker>{{cite journal|author=Baker, E. G|year=1896|title=New African Plants|journal=Journal of Botany, British and Foreign|volume=34|pages=53\u201357|publisher=West, Newman & Co|url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/item/35905#page/68/mode/1up}}</ref> [[Emilio Chiovenda]] later described another specimen from Kenya as ''Moringa streptocarpa''. In 1957, Georg Cufodontis identified these specimens to be [[Morphology (biology)|morphologically]] similar and designated them as ''Moringa stenopetala'', the officially accepted species name.<ref name=Habtemariam>{{cite book|authors=Habtemariam, S.|year=2017|title=The African and Arabian Moringa Species|chapter=1: ''Moringa stenopetala''\u2014Botanical and Ecological Perspectives|publisher=Elsevier|isbn=9780081022948|edition=1|pages=3\u201312}}</ref> The specific epithet ''stenopetala'' is derived from the [[Greek language|Greek]] words ''stenos'' (narrow or straight) and ''petalum'' (petal), a reference to the shape of its [[petal]]s.<ref name=botdict>{{cite web|url=http://www.botanicalepithets.net/dictionary/dictionary.171.html|work=Dictionary of Botanical Epithets|title=stella - stolonifer|year=2019|accessdate=2019-08-05}}</ref>\n\nAlong with at least twelve other species, ''M. stenopetala'' belongs to the [[Monotypic taxon|monotypic genus]] of ''[[Moringa]]'', which itself is the sole representative of the [[Moringaceae]] family. Researchers have divided these species into three distinct groups: ''Moringa'' with eight, ''Dysmoringa'' with one, and ''Donadsonia'' with four.<ref name=Habtemariam /><ref name=Olson2001>{{cite book|authors=Lianli, L.; Olson, M.E|year=2001|chapter=Moringaceae|editors=P.H. Raven, I. Al-Shehbaz & G. Zhu|title=Flora of China (Brassicaceae through Saxifragaceae)|series=Flora of China|volume=8|page=196|publisher=Missouri Botanical Garden Press|isbn=9780915279937}}</ref> ''M. stenopetala'' belongs to the latter group, along with ''[[Moringa drouhardii|M. drouhardii]]'' and ''[[Moringa hildebrandtii|M. hildebrandtii]]'', characterized by winged seeds and (almost) regular flowers with short [[Receptacle (botany)|receptacles]] and [[Ovary (botany)#Superior ovary|superior ovaries]].<ref name=Habtemariam />\n\n''M. stenopetala'' is known under various [[Common name|vernacular name]]s throughout its native regions, including ''(h)aleko'' in the [[Gidole]] language ([[Gamo Gofa Zone|Gamo Gofa]]), ''shelagda'' or ''telchada'' in the [[Konso language]], and ''Shiferaw'' in [[Amharic]]. In English, it is most commonly known as the African Moringa or cabbage tree, though these names may be shared with other ''Moringa'' species from Africa.<ref name=Habtemariam />\n\n==Description==\n[[File:First illustration of Moringa stenopetala (basonym Donaldsonia), from E. G. Baker's 1896 original description.jpg|165px|thumb|left|Illustration from the ''[[Journal of Botany, British and Foreign]]'' in 1896]] \n''Moringa stenopetala'' is a [[perennial]] tree with a [[shrub]]by, rounded [[Habit (biology)|habit]],<ref name=seednutrition>{{cite journal|title=Characterisation of ''Moringa stenopetala'' seed oil variety \"Marigat\" from island Kokwa|authors=Lalas, S.; Tsaknis, J.; Sflomos, K.|year=2003|journal=European Journal of Lipid Science and Technology|volume=105|issue=1|pages=23\u201331|doi=10.1002/ejlt.200390002}}</ref> growing to a height of {{convert|6|-|12|m|0|abbr=on}} in all but the most exceptional cases where it may reach   {{convert|15|m|0|abbr=on}} high.<ref name=WAF /><ref name=ECHO>{{cite web|url=https://www.echocommunity.org/en/resources/8b52cd0f-d585-45df-905e-a93fa631a8bf.pdf|title=African Moringa Tree|work=Echo Plant Information Sheet|year=2019|publisher=ECHO}}</ref> [[wikt:caudiciform|Caudiciform]] or \"bottle shaped\",<ref name=PROTA2>{{cite book|title=Plant Resources of Tropical Africa|series=Plant Resources of Tropical Africa (PROTA)|volume=2: Vegetables|editors=G.J.H. Grubben & O.A. Denton|year=2004|publisher=Earthprint Limited|author=Bosch, C.H.|chapter=Moringa|pages=395\u2212398|isbn=9789057821486}}</ref> the trunk is bloated at the base and habitually [[Tree fork|forked]],<ref name=WAF /> with a diameter up to {{convert|1|m|0|abbr=on}}. The bark is smooth and whitish to light gray or silver, harboring soft wood underneath.<ref name=PROTA2 /> The crown is sprawling and heavily branched; younger shoots are characterized by a dense, velvety [[indumentum|pubescence]].<ref name=floraEA>{{cite book|title=Flora of Tropical East Africa|chapter=Moringaceae|series=Flora of Tropical East Africa|publisher=CRC Press|year=1986|editor=R. M. Polhill|author=Verdcourt, B.|issue=80|isbn=978-1842463970}}</ref>\n\nThe leaves are light green when mature,<ref name=PGR-Ethiopia>{{cite book|chapter=Konso agriculture and its plant genetic resources|title=Plant Genetic Resources of Ethiopia|year=1991|publisher=Cambridge University Press|editors=J.M.M. Engels, J.G. Hawkes & M. Worede|authors=Engels, J.M.M.; Goettsch, E.|edition=1|isbn=978-0521384568}}</ref> up to {{convert|55|cm|0|abbr=on}} long, and [[Phyllotaxis#Leaf arrangement|attached alternately]] to the stem by short [[Petiole (botany)|petiole]]s.<ref name=PROTA2 /> They are bi- or tri[[Pinnation|pinnate]] in composition, with about five pairs of pinnae and three to nine [[Leaflet (botany)|leaflets]] on each pinna.<ref name=WAF>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldagroforestry.org/treedb/AFTPDFS/Moringa_stenopetala.PDF|title=''Moringa stenopetala''|work=Agroforestry Database 4.0|year=2009|publisher=World Agroforestry}}</ref> Each leaflet is {{convert|3.5|-|6.5|cm|1|abbr=on}} \u00d7 {{convert|2|-|3.5|cm|1|abbr=on}} in size and [[wikt:elliptical|elliptical]] to [[wikt:ovate|ovate]] in shape, with an [[Leaf shapes|acute]] tip and a round-to-[[wikt:cuneate|cuneate]] base.<ref name=PROTA2 /> [[Stipule]]-like [[Extrafloral nectaries|extrafloral nectaries]] are typically present at the base of the leaves.<ref name=PROTA2 /><ref name=bottleforms>{{cite web|url=http://www.mobot.org/gradstudents/olson/bottlespecies.html|title=Bottle Tree Form|website=Moringa Home Page|publisher=Missouri Botanical Garden|year=1999|author=Olson, M.}}</ref>\n\n''M. stenopetala'' features a busy, aromatic [[inflorescence]], organized as dense [[panicle]]s up to {{convert|60|cm|0|abbr=on}} long. The individual flowers are [[Plant reproductive morphology#bisexual|bisexual]], [[Radial symmetry|radially symmetrical]], and [[Merosity|pentamerous]]. The [[Calyx (botany)|calyx]] is [[wikt:polysepalous|polysepalous]] and cream colored, sometimes flushed pink, with {{convert|4|-|7|mm|1|abbr=on}} long [[sepal]]s. The [[Catacorolla|corolla]] is [[wikt:polypetalous|polypetalous]] and variably white, pale-yellow or yellow-green; its petals are roughly oblong in shape and {{convert|8|-|10|mm|1|abbr=on}} in length.<ref name=PROTA2 /> Each flower features five [[stamen]]s with white {{convert|4|-|6.5|mm|1|abbr=on}} long filaments and yellow {{convert|2|mm|1|abbr=on}} long anthers, as well as an indeterminate number of shorter [[staminode]]s.<ref name=floraEA /> The [[Ovary (botany)|ovary]] is densely haired and [[Superior ovary|superior]], {{convert|2|mm|1|abbr=on}} long and [[wikt:ovoid|ovoid]] in shape, transitioning to a smooth cylindrical [[Stylodia|style]] sans [[Stigma (botany)#Shape|stigmatic lobes]].<ref name=PROTA2 /> \n\nThe fruits comprise {{convert|19.7|-|50|cm|1|abbr=on}} \u00d7 {{convert|1.8|-|4|cm|1|abbr=on}} elongate pods which are initially twisted but gradually straight, sometimes [[wikt:torose|torose]] (bulbous) around the encapsulated seeds.<ref name=floraEA /> Young pods are bright green,<ref name=moringaceae /> maturing to a reddish coloration with a grayish bloom.<ref name=floraEA /> The fruits are [[Dehiscence (botany)|dehiscent]], splitting open along three prominent [[Glossary of botanical terms#valve|valves]] when mature and releasing up to 20 seeds each.<ref name=seeds>{{cite journal|title=The potential of some ''Moringa'' species for seed oil production|journal=Agriculture|year=2018|volume=8|issue=10|page=150|authors=Boukandoul, S.; Casal, S.; Zaidi, F.|doi=10.3390/agriculture8100150}}</ref> Covered by a cream to brownish husk with three papery wings, the seeds are oblong to triangular, {{convert|2.5|-|3.5|cm|1|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|1.5|-|2|cm|1|abbr=on}} wide,<ref name=PROTA2 /> containing a smooth, whitish grey kernel.<ref name=seeds />\n\n== Distribution, habitat and ecology ==\nSparsely [[Range (biology)|distributed]] across the [[Horn of Africa]],<ref name=bottleforms /> ''Moringa stenopetala'' is [[Endemism|endemic]] to southern [[Ethiopia]], northern [[Kenya]],<ref name=PROTA2 /> and possibly [[Somalia]].<ref name=WAF /><ref name=Star>{{cite journal|title=\n''Moringa stenopetala'' tree species improved selected soil properties and socio-economic benefits in Tigray, northern Ethiopia|journal=Science, Technology and Arts Research Journal|year=2015|authors= Abay, A.; Birhane, E.; Taddesse, T.; Hagdu, K.M.|doi=10.4314/star.v4i2.10|volume=4|issue=2|pages=68\u201378}}</ref> Extant populations are poorly documented,<ref name=bottleforms /> but have been identified in the wild in at least five localities across the [[Great Rift Valley, Kenya|Kenyan Rift Valley]]<ref name=PROTA2 />\u2014one on [[Ol Kokwe Island]] in [[Lake Baringo]] and four around the shores of [[Lake Turkana]].<ref name=bottleforms /> Records of wild specimens from other east African countries, including [[Djibouti]], [[Sudan]], and [[Uganda]], have been deemed unreliable.   ''M. stenopetala'' trees are widely cultivated in southern Ethiopia, where they were likely sourced from a now-extinct population near [[Lake Chew Bahir]].<ref name=PROTA2/> Since modern times, the species has steadily been [[Introduced species|introduced]] across tropical Africa: it is found as far west as [[Senegal]] and as far south as [[Malawi]].<ref name=PROTA2 /> \n\n[[File:Ethiopia - Mature Moringa stenopetala tree - March 2011.jpg|thumb|right|[[Habit (biology)|Habit]] in the [[Gurage Zone]], Ethiopia]] \nIn the wild, ''M. stenopetala'' occurs in various [[habitats]] with different [[Bioclimatology|bioclimatic]] conditions and [[elevation]]s of 400\u20131,200&nbsp;m (1,300\u20133,900&nbsp;ft).<ref name=WAF /><ref name=floraEA /> Its distribution range is [[Arid climate|arid]] to [[Semi-arid climate|semi-arid]], with an average annual rainfall of 500\u20131,400&nbsp;mm (20\u201355&nbsp;in) and mean temperatures of 24\u201330&nbsp;\u00b0C (75\u201386&nbsp;\u00b0F).<ref name=WAF /> Often growing near bodies of water,<ref name=PROTA2/> wild trees have been observed in [[dryland]]s, [[shrubland]]s, and [[woodland]]s,<ref name=floraEA /> where they may form [[Association (ecology)|associations]] with ''[[Acacia tortilis]]'', ''[[Delonix elata]]'' and ''[[Commiphora]]'' spp.,<ref name=WAF /> as well as in [[wetland]]s, often associated with riverside species from ''[[Hyphaene]]'', ''[[Salvadora (plant)|Salvadora]]'' and ''[[Cadaba]]''.<ref name=floraEA /> These regions are characterized by rocky or sandy soils,<ref name=PROTA2/><ref name=moringaceae /> with good [[drainage]] and neutral to slightly acidic or alkaline [[soil pH|soil reaction]].<ref name=WAF /> The species is, however, known for its ability to subsist on a wide variety of (possibly very harsh) soil conditions;<ref name=WAF /><ref name=Star /> mature trees can even improve the [[soil fertility|fertility]] of the surrounding topsoil with their tendency to shed considerable amounts of [[Soil organic matter|organic matter]].<ref name=Star /> \n\nLike its African relatives, ''M. stenopetala'' is well adapted to the severe heat and drought that characterize its native landscapes,<ref name=moringaceae /> where, given proper shading, it may survive temperatures up to 48&nbsp;\u00b0C (118&nbsp;\u00b0F).<ref name=Star /> Developing early, the tuberous roots and bloated trunk form a prominent [[storage organ]],<ref name=moringaceae /> which allows the plant to preserve water and thrive in drier climates.<ref name=Habtemariam /> Although drought-[[deciduous]], shedding its leaves towards the end of very prolonged dry seasons, it habitually grows as an [[evergreen]] under more moderate conditions.<ref name=Habtemariam /><ref name=lostcrops /> Light frost is tolerated, although persistent cold temperatures at higher growing elevations may eventually cause the tree to wither down to the base of its trunk, as well as inducing [[Seed dormancy|dormancy]] in seeds.<ref name=WAF /><ref name=Star/>\n\n''M. stenopetala'' trees live between 60 and 100&nbsp;years, often with sustained productivity until the end of their lifespan.<ref name=seifu>{{cite journal|authors=Seifu, E.|year=2014|title=Actual and potential applications of ''Moringa stenopetala'', underutilized indigenous vegetable of Southern Ethiopia: A review|journal=International Journal of Agricultural and Food Research|volume=3|issue=4|pages=8\u201319|ISSN=1929-0969}}</ref>  It is a quickly developing species; young plants can grow as high as 3&nbsp;m (10&nbsp;ft) in their first year and typically reach [[Plant reproduction|reproductive maturity]] after 2.5&nbsp;years.<ref name=PROTA2 /> From there on, the plants often continue to flower and fruit year-round.<ref name=Star /> The flowers emit a sweet fragrance that encourages [[pollination]] by birds and insects alike.<ref name=moringaceae>{{cite book|author=Kubitzki, K.|year=2003|chapter=Moringaceae|editors=K. Kubitzki & C. Bayer|title=Flowering Plants \u00b7 Dicotyledons|series=The Families and Genera of Vascular Plants|volume=5|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-3-662-07255-4}}</ref> Mature seeds may be dispersed by either wind or water.<ref name=moringaceae /> The foliage provides nutritious [[forage]] for both wild and domesticated [[ruminants]], whereas the flowers serve as an important source of [[nectar]] for [[honeybees]].{{Citation needed|date=December 2019|reason=removed citation to predatory publisher content}}\n\n==Cultivation==\n''Moringa stenopetala'' was planted by agriculturalists on the complex system of [[Terrace (agriculture)|terraces]] built high up in the [[Ethiopian Highlands]], where they became domesticated and were bred to improve productivity, the taste of their leaves, and the size of their seeds. Since then, the improved trees have been introduced into other areas such as the [[Great Rift Valley, Kenya|Kenyan Rift Valley]].<ref>{{cite journal |author=Jahn, S.A.A.|year=1991 |title=The traditional domestication of a multipurpose tree ''Moringa stenopetala'' (Bak. f.) Cuf. in the Ethiopian Rift Valley |journal=Ambio |volume=20 |issue=6 |pages=244\u2013247 |jstor=4313833 }}</ref>\n\nIn present-day Ethiopia, ''M. stenopetala'' is mostly known for its importance as a nutritious [[vegetable]] food crop in the terraced fields of [[Konso]], where it is cultivated for its leaves and pods.<ref name=PROTA2 /> [[Plant propagation|Propagation]] is easiest from seeds,<ref name=Habtemariam /> although plants grown from [[Cutting (plant)|cuttings]] may flower and fruit sooner (within several months).<ref name=lostcrops>{{cite book|title=Vegetables|series=Lost Crops of Africa|volume=2|chapter=14: Moringa|year=2006|publisher=The National Academies Press|isbn=978-0-309-16454-2|pages=246\u2013267}}</ref> Kept moist and in full sun, seeds placed 1\u20132 cm deep in well-draining soil typically [[Germination|germinate]] about a week after sowing. Temperatures for optimal growth and production in the Ethiopian Rift Valley range from 15&nbsp;\u00b0C (59&nbsp;\u00b0F) to 33&nbsp;\u00b0C (91&nbsp;\u00b0F), corresponding with elevations of 1,150\u20131,800&nbsp;m (3,775\u20135,900&nbsp;ft). Collection of the leaves and fruits may start after two years, although traditional farmers usually wait 5 to 6 years before harvesting.<ref name=Habtemariam />\n\n==Culinary use and nutrition ==\n<!--{{Nutritional value\n| name = Nutritional composition of ''Moringa stenopetala'' leaf, raw\n| kJ = 295\n| protein = 9.0\n| fat = 5.8\n| carbs = 51.8\n| vitC_mg = 28.07\n| calcium_mg = 793\n| iron_mg = 3.08\n| phosphorus_mg = 65.6\n| potassium_mg = 453.0\n| sodium_mg = 403.5\n| zinc_mg = 0.53\n}} -->\n\nThe leaves, seeds, flowers and young pods of ''M. stenopetala'' are all edible and commonly feature in dishes across its distribution range. Over 5&nbsp;million people are estimated to consume ''M. stenopetala'' on a regular basis;<ref name=PROTA2 /> it is especially favored by various ethnic groups of Ethiopia's [[Southern Nations, Nationalities, and Peoples' Region|SNNP Region]].<ref name=PROTA2 /><ref name=Kumssa /><ref name=dishes />\n\n=== Leaves ===\n[[File:Moringa stenopetala.jpg|thumb|Leaves on a young plant, showing a [[Pinnation|pinnate]] composition]]\nLike ''M. oleifera'', the leaves of ''M. stenopetala'' make for a nutrient-dense edible green. A [[nutrition analysis]] of an Ethiopian sample yielded 28.44&nbsp;g of protein, 0.7&nbsp;g of fat, 38.49&nbsp;g of [[carbohydrate]]s and 11.62&nbsp;g of crude fiber per 100&nbsp;g dry weight, with a mean energy value of 274&nbsp;[[Calorie|kcal]] (1,146 [[Kilojoule|kJ]]).{{cn|date=January 2020}} Raw leaves are rich in [[vitamin C]] (28&nbsp;mg/100&nbsp;g), a good source of [[vitamin A]], and comparable to [[cruciferous vegetables]] for their significant mineral content (such as [[calcium]], [[iron]] and [[phosphorus]]).<ref name=WAF /><ref name=PROTA2 /> Within the ''Moringa'' genus, ''M. stenopetala'' leaves are highest in [[sulfur]] and remarkably rich in protein.<ref name=olson2016>{{cite journal|title=Leaf protein and mineral concentrations across the \u201cmiracle tree\u201d genus ''Moringa''|authors=Olson, M.E.; Sankaran, R.P.; Fahey, J.W.; Grusak, M.A.; Odee, D.; Nouman, W.|year=2016|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0159782|journal=PLOS One|volume=11|issue=7|page=e0159782|pmc=4961408}}</ref> Variables that may affect the nutrient \u2013 particularly mineral \u2013 compositions of ''M. stenopetala'' include the season,<ref name=elevation>{{cite journal|title=Effects of elevation and season on nutrient composition of leaves and green pods of ''Moringa stenopetala'' and ''Moringa oleifera''|authors=Melesse, A.; Steingass, H.; Boguhn, J.; Schollenberger, M.; Rodehutscord, M.|journal=Agroforestry Systems|year=2012|volume=86|issue=3|pages=505\u2013518|doi=10.1007/s10457-012-}}</ref> growing elevations,<ref name=elevation /> and soil type.<ref name=Kumssa /> During the dry season, the average southern Ethiopian adult eats 150&nbsp;g of fresh leaves per day, providing 19% of their energy and 30% of their protein requirements.<ref name=PROTA2 />\n\nThe taste of the leaves ranges from bitter to sweet, may vary per tree, and is described as more pleasant during the dry season. The leaflets are stripped from the [[rachis]] and eaten either raw or cooked like [[cabbage]],<ref name=PROTA2 /> inspiring the common name \"cabbage tree\".<ref name=cabbage>{{cite book|chapter=A multipurpose cabbage tree (''Moringa stenopetala''): Production, utilization and marketing in SNNPR, Ethiopia|work=Acta Horticulturae|title=International Symposium on the Socio-Economic Impact of Modern Vegetable Production Technology in Tropical Asia|number=809|isbn=9789066057210|year=2009|volume=1|pages=115\u2013120|authors=Tenaye, A.; Geta, E.; Hebana, E.|editors=H. Jaenicke, J. Ganry, I. Hoeschle-Zeledon & R. Kahane}}</ref> They may be served with bread as a nutritious addition to many meals.<ref name=Kumssa>{{cite journal|title=Challenges and opportunities for ''Moringa'' growers in southern Ethiopia and Kenya|authors=Kumssa, D.B.; Joy, E.J.M.; Young, S.D.; Odee, D.W.; Ander, E.L.; Magare, C.; Gitu, J.; Broadley, M.R.|year=2017|doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0187651|journal=PLOS One|volume=12|issue=11|page=e0187651}}</ref><ref name=dishes>{{cite thesis|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/c7d7/e4a605e3093a61c3ad9e538cbafd2c465b6d.pdf|title=Usage and acceptance of ''Moringa stenopetala'' in the diet in Ethiopia|year=2012|author=Gl\u00e6rum, N.|type=MSc|publisher=University of Agder}}</ref> In the Konso region of Ethiopia, balls of mixed flours \u2013 and sometimes cereals \u2013 are typically boiled in salt water and served alongside the leaves.<ref name=PROTA2 /> The [[Silt\u02bce people]] use [[cornmeal]] as the principle flour, and include onions and chilies to create a dish called ''kurkufa''. In a variation of this preparation, known as ''fosesae'', the cornmeal is first mixed with water to create a doughy consistency, and then cooked with the leaves and spices.<ref name=dishes /> Dried, crushed leaves may be added to ''chegga'', a traditional [[sorghum]] brew of the [[Dirashe special woreda|Dirashe people]].<ref name=Kumssa />\n\n=== Other parts ===\nBecause the fruits are slightly bitter, even when young, they are normally prepared only in times when other crops are scarce.<ref name=PROTA2 />\nThe flowers may also be boiled or eaten fresh.<ref name=Kumssa /> The seeds yield an aromatic, edible oil that may be used for cooking or as a dressing for salads.{{Citation needed|date=December 2019|reason=removed citation to predatory publisher content}}\n\n==Other uses==\n[[File:Moringa stenopetala nursery in Gurage Zone, Ethiopia.jpg|thumb|left|''M. stenopetala'' [[Plant nursery|nursery]] in the [[Gurage Zone]] of Ethiopia]]\nIt is used for shading of ''[[Capsicum]]'' and ''[[Sorghum]]'' crops, and as a [[companion planting|companion plant]].<ref name=grin1/>\nA 2015 survey across Derashe and Konso villages found that most households grow ''M. stenopetala'' trees, having done so their entire life; all had consumed the tree as food, many relied on it for income, and some used it for medicinal purposes.<ref name=Kumssa />\n\nAnother use is the clarification and purification of water to make it potable. A powder made by grinding the seeds is found to be more effective at coagulating substances in suspension than the seeds of ''M. oleifera'', which is used for this purpose in India.<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.3362/0262-8104.1985.019 |title=Water purification with ''Moringa'' seeds |year=1985 |last1=Desa |first1=D. |journal=Waterlines |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=22\u20133}}</ref> When powdered, the tree bark has [[Adsorption|adsorbent]] properties which may be effective in industrial wastewater treatments.<ref name=barkpowder>{{cite journal|title=''Moringa stenopetala'' bark: A novel green adsorbent for the removal of metal ions from industrial effluents|authors=Kebede, T.G.; Dube, S.; Mengistie, A.A.; Nkambule, T.T.I.; Nindia, M.M.|year=2018|journal=Physics and Chemistry of the Earth|volume=107|pages=45\u201357|doi=10.1016/j.pce.2018.08.002}}</ref>\n\n===Folk medicine===\n''M. stenopetala'' has a history of purported applications in [[folk medicine]] throughout its native range. The [[Ilchamus people]] of Kenya chew or boil the roots for cough relief and strength. Among the [[Turkana people]], those with [[leprosy]] drink a [[decoction]] of the leaves.<ref name=PROTA2 /> The macerated roots and/or leaves are boiled in water and taken as a herbal remedy throughout southern Ethiopia for various conditions, such as [[malaria]], [[diarrhea]], and [[dysentery]].<ref name=PROTA2 /><ref name=ethiopia>{{cite book|author=Mekonnen, Y.|chapter=The multi-purpose Moringa tree: Ethiopia|pages=111\u2013117|title=Examples of the Development of Pharmaceutical Products from Medicinal Plants|publisher=United Nations Development Programme|year=2005|volume=10|series=[http://www.esupp.unsouthsouth.org/gssd-academy-solutions/ Sharing Innovative Experiences]|issn=1728-4171}}</ref> The [[Konso people]] use the dried leaves to make a tea or herbal extract, which they believe to have a soothing effect on respiratory ailments.<ref name=PGR-Ethiopia /> Sap extracts from the branches and leaves may be applied externally by the Dirashe people to promote hygiene.<ref name=Kumssa />\n\n== Research ==\nLike its sister species ''M. oleifera'', ''Moringa stenopetala'' is under [[basic research]] to determine whether it has bioactive properties;<ref name=PROTA2 /> its potential effects in humans remain unconfirmed.\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160\">\n\nFile:Moringa stenopetala tree trunk, Koko Crater Botanical Garden.jpg|The bloated water-storing trunk of a fully grown tree at [[Koko Crater Botanical Garden]] on [[Oahu]], [[Hawaii]]\nFile:Moringa stenopetala seed pods in tree.jpg|Branches with foliage and fruits at Koko Crater Botanical Garden\nFile:Moringa stenopetala open seed pod.jpg|Open ''M. stenopetala'' fruit pod revealing mature seeds inside\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\nOther African moringa species:\n* ''[[Moringa drouhardii]]\n* ''[[Moringa hildebrandtii]]\n* ''[[Moringa ovalifolia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q3021919}}\n\n[[Category:Moringa|streptocarpa]]\n[[Category:Flora of Kenya]]\n[[Category:Trees of Ethiopia]]\n[[Category:Trees of Africa]]\n[[Category:Fruits originating in Africa]]\n[[Category:Tropical fruit]]\n[[Category:Tropical agriculture]]\n[[Category:Plants described in 1896]]\n[[Category:Afromontane flora]]\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moringa_stenopetala"}
{"title_page": "SpaceX CRS-21", "text_new": "{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name          = SpaceX CRS-21\n| image         = CARGO DRAGON 2.jpg\n| image_caption = Rendering of Cargo Dragon 2\n| COSPAR_ID     = \n| SATCAT        = \n\n| mission_type    = [[ISS]] resupply\n| operator        = [[SpaceX]]\n| manufacturer    = [[SpaceX]]\n| spacecraft      = [[Dragon 2]] C2??\n| spacecraft_type = [[Dragon 2|Cargo Dragon]]\n\n| launch_mass  = <!--{{convert||kg|abbr=on}}-->\n| dry_mass     = 9525 kg <!--spacecraft mass in orbit without fuel-->\n| payload_mass = <!--Mass of cargo carried by spacecraft, or total mass of instrumentation/equipment/experiments for mission-->\n| dimensions   = Height: 8.1 m<br/>Diameter: 4 m <!--body dimensions and solar array span-->\n| power        = <!--end-of-life power, in watts-->\n\n| launch_date       = 30 October 2020 (planned) <ref name=SFN/>\n| launch_rocket     = [[Falcon 9 Block 5|Falcon 9]]\n| launch_site       = [[Kennedy Space Center]], [[LC-39A]]\n| launch_contractor = [[SpaceX]]\n\n| orbit_epoch       = \n| orbit_reference   = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]]\n| orbit_regime      = [[Low Earth orbit|Low Earth]]\n| orbit_periapsis   = \n| orbit_apoapsis    = \n| orbit_inclination = 51.6\u00b0\n| orbit_period      = \n| apsis             = gee\n\n| docking = {{Infobox spaceflight/Dock\n  | docking_target = [[International Space Station|ISS]]\n  | docking_type   = \n  | docking_port   = ''[[Harmony (ISS module)|Harmony]]'' or ''[[Unity (ISS module)|Unity]]''\n  | docking_date   =  2020\n  | undocking_date = \n  | release_date   = \n  | time_docked    = \n }}\n\n<!--Cargo parameters-->| payload_items = <!--Major individual items (e.g. satellites deployed, etc)-->\n| cargo_mass         = <!--{{convert|0|kg|abbr=on}}--><!--Mass of the cargo aboard-->\n| cargo_mass_press   = <!--{{convert|0|kg|abbr=on}}--><!--Mass of pressurised cargo-->\n| cargo_mass_unpress = <!--Mass of unpressurised cargo (e.g. Dragon Trunk)-->\n| cargo_mass_fuel    = <!--{{convert|0|kg|abbr=on}}--><!--Mass of fuel transferred from spacecraft's tanks-->\n| cargo_mass_gas     = <!--{{convert|0|kg|abbr=on}}--><!--Mass of gasses transferred (e.g. oxygen)-->\n| cargo_mass_water   = <!--{{convert|0|kg|abbr=on}}--><!--Mass of water transferred-->\n\n| programme        = [[Commercial Resupply Services]]\n| previous_mission = [[Cygnus NG-14]]\n| next_mission     = [[SpaceX CRS-22]]\n}}\n\n'''SpaceX CRS-21''', also known as '''SpaceX-21''', is a [[Commercial Resupply Services|Commercial Resupply Service mission]] to the [[International Space Station]] planned to be launched on 30 October 2020.<ref name=SFN/><ref name=seds-issschedule/> The mission is contracted by [[NASA]] and will be flown by [[SpaceX]] using a [[Dragon 2|Cargo Dragon]]. This will be the first flight for SpaceX under NASA's [[Commercial Resupply Services#Commercial Resupply Services phase 2|CRS-2]] contract awarded in January 2016.\n\n==Cargo Dragon==\nSpaceX plans to reuse the Cargo Dragons up to five (5) times. The Crew Dragon capsules used on missions with astronauts, are not planned to be reused (initially). The Cargo Dragon will launch without SuperDraco abort engines, without seats, cockpit controls and the life support system required to sustain astronauts in space.<ref name=teslarati-20200217/> This newer design provides several benefits, including a faster process to recover, refurbish and re-fly versus the earlier Dragon CRS design used for ISS cargo missions.<ref name=sfn20190802/>\n\nBeginning with the CRS-21 mission, the new Dragon Cargo capsules will splash down under parachutes in the Atlantic Ocean east of Florida, rather than the current recovery zone in the Pacific Ocean west of Baja California. This was a NASA preference, added to CRS-2.<ref name=sfn20190802/><ref name=nasa-oif-18016/>\n\n==Primary payload==\nNASA contracted for the CRS-21 mission from SpaceX and therefore determines the primary payload, date of launch, and [[orbital elements|orbital parameters]] for the [[SpaceX Dragon|Cargo Dragon]].<ref name=NASA-SpX21-Overview/>\n\n* '''Science investigations:'''   {{cvt|0|lb|order=flip}}\n* '''Vehicle hardware:'''         {{cvt|0|lb|order=flip}}\n* '''Crew supplies:'''            {{cvt|0|lb|order=flip}}\n* '''Spacewalk equipment:'''      {{cvt|0|lb|order=flip}}\n* '''Computer resources:'''       {{cvt|0|lb|order=flip}}\n* '''External payloads:''' BISHOP {{cvt|0|lb|order=flip}}\n\n''' [[Bishop Airlock Module|Bishop]]''' formerly known as NanoRacks Airlock Module, is a small commercial airlock module attached to Node 3 ([[Tranquility (ISS module)|Tranquility module]]) of the ISS.<ref name=Bishop2020/> The NanoRacks Airlock Module will offer five times the satellite deployment volume than current opportunities (Japanese [[Kibo (ISS module)|Kibo module]] airlock) available today. Nanoracks is the prime contractor, with Thales Alenia Space building the pressurized shell and Boeing providing the berthing mechanism.<ref name=Gunter-20200211/>\n\nCubesats planned for this mission: CAPSat, CySat 1, NEUTRON 1, PR-CuNaR 2, SPACE-HAUC, SPOC, TJREVERB, Alpha.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Uncrewed spaceflights to the International Space Station]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2|refs=\n<ref name=SFN>{{cite web|url=https://spaceflightnow.com/launch-schedule/|title=Launch Schedule|publisher=SpaceflightNow|accessdate=5 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=teslarati-20200217>{{cite web|url=https://www.teslarati.com/spacex-no-crew-dragon-spaceship-reuse-nasa-astronaut-launches/cargo-dragon-2-required-modifications/|title=Dragon 2 modifications to Carry Cargo for CRS-2 missions|publisher=SpaceX/Teslarati|accessdate=17 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=seds-issschedule>{{cite web|url=http://spider.seds.org/shuttle/iss-sche.html|title=International Space Station Flight Schedule|author=Frommert, Hartmut|accessdate=12 February 2020|publisher=SEDS USA : Students for the Exploration and Development of Space}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=sfn20190802>{{cite web|url= https://spaceflightnow.com/2019/08/02/spacex-to-begin-flights-under-new-cargo-resupply-contract-next-year/|title=SpaceX to begin flights under new cargo resupply contract next year|author=Clark, Stephen|publisher=SpaceflightNow|date=2 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=nasa-oif-18016>{{cite report|url=https://oig.nasa.gov/docs/IG-18-016.pdf |title=Audit of Commercial Resupply Services to the International Space Center |author=OIG Staff |publisher=NASA Office of Inspector General |page=24 |date=26 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=NASA-SpX21-Overview>{{cite web|url= https://www.nasa.gov/sites/default/files/atoms/files/spacex_crs-21_mission_overview.pdf|title=SpX-21 Mission Overview |publisher=NASA|date=26 October 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Bishop2020>{{cite web |url= https://nanoracks.com/products/airlock/|title=Nanoracks' Bishop Airlock|publisher=Nanoracks|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=Gunter-20200211>{{cite web|url=https://space.skyrocket.de/doc_sdat/bishop.htm|title=Bishop|publisher=Gunter's Space Page|date=11 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.nasa.gov/ NASA]\n* [http://www.spacex.com/dragon SpaceX official page for the Dragon spacecraft]\n* [https://nanoracks.com/products/airlock/ Nanoracks Airlock Module: Bishop]\n* [https://www.gfz-potsdam.de/en/section/space-geodetic-techniques/projects/geros-iss/ GNSS Remote Sensing aboard the ISS]\n\n{{Portalbar|Spaceflight}}\n{{Dragon spaceflights}}\n{{Falcon rocket launches}}\n{{Unmanned ISS resupply flights}}\n{{Future spaceflights}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:CRS 021}}\n[[Category:Dragon 2]]\n[[Category:2020 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:SpaceX payloads contracted by NASA]]\n[[Category:Supply vehicles for the International Space Station]]\n[[Category:2020 in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox spaceflight\n| name          = SpaceX CRS-21\n| image         = CARGO DRAGON 2.jpg\n| image_caption = Rendering of Cargo Dragon 2\n| COSPAR_ID     = \n| SATCAT        = \n\n| miss